For anyone who found this during a google search for how to get the arrow to show up on a TreeItem that has no children, this is what I learned.

All you have to do is Override the isLeaf() method of TreeItem and have it return false then the arrow will show up.

If you wanted a method that only returns empty TreeItems with the arrow enabled, you could do it like this (and I chose String for simplicity but using a custom class would be fine as well):

    private TreeItem&lt;String&gt; emptyArrowItem(String itemsString) {
        return new TreeItem&lt;&gt;(itemsString) {
            @Override public boolean isLeaf() {
                return false;
            }
        }
    }


However, if you wanted to use a custom class for TreeItem and then base whether or not it&#39;s an empty Item with the expand arrow showing using that class, you could do it like this:

    private TreeItem&lt;CustomTreeItem&gt; createItem(final CustomTreeItem customTreeItem) {
    
        return new TreeItem&lt;&gt;(customTreeItem) {
            
            private boolean isLeaf;
            private boolean isFirstTimeLeaf = true;
    
         @Override public boolean isLeaf() {
                if (isFirstTimeLeaf) {
                    isFirstTimeLeaf = false;
                    CustomTreeItem cti = getValue();
                    isLeaf = cti.isEmptyItem();
                }
                 return isLeaf;
            }
        };
    }


This example comes straight out of the example given in [the JavaDocs][1] for the TreeItem class, only I simplified it quite a bit which makes it a bit easier to understand.


  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/javafx/api/javafx/scene/control/TreeItem.html

